1 Summary

There has been major impact on global economy with the COVID-19 pandemic. To understand how financial volatity can be studied through foreign exchange rate data, this final project performs time series analysis to implement POMP and GARCH. UK pound or GBP/USD is taken for the purpose of study. Goal of this project are as follows:

  • To experiment with Partially Observed Markov Process (POMP) and investgate how it can be used to understand the volatility of financial markets or foreign exchange rates.

  • The models we develop do not quite have the standard POMP structure, since the observed variable (Exchange Rate ) has some effect on the dynamics of the latent variable (volatility). Therefore I aim to learn how to adapt standard POMP methods for this situation.

  • To understand and compare POMP and GARCH model.

Geometric Brownian Motion, is taken as mathematical model to study foreign exchange data of GBP/USD. Liklihood slicing is done to select optimal values for 3 parameters. I evaluate the likelihood, together with a standard error, using particle filters at each point estimate. Global search with randomized starting values is performed. Its log likelihood is compared with that of local search. I have then compared POMP model with GARCH(0,1) as a benchmark. POMP is favoured due to its ease in interpretatbility and because its log liklihood is not much statistically different from GARCH log likelihood. Diagnoistics is performed to see if it can be improved to beat the GARCH model.

2 Introduction

Exchange rate in the COVID-19 pandemic, are important signal to global policymaker of underlying health of economy. Economists have been trying to study the foreign exchange rate for years. From some research paper, Geometric Brownian Motion (GBM) has been proved useful in simulating financial data (Brewer, K., Feng, Y., & Kwan, C, 2012). Gerber, for example, points out in the paper that GBM could be used to model assets and liability (Gerber, H., & Shiu, E., 2003). Motivated by those research papaers, I want to experiment with time series models and technique on the of foreign exchange rate.

I want to address the question whether GBM POMP is suitable for fitting the UK pound GBM/USD exchange rate. I have used POMP model and Particle filter approach to get unbiased Monte Carlo estimate of log likelihood. I further evaluated my selection of model with the help methods like Likelihood surface evaluation and global search evaluuation. Also, I build the GARCH model and calculate its log likelihood and perform diagnostics like QQ plot and ACF plot to see the validity of models assumption.

3 Dataset

Dataset used in the project is from the website of Federal Reserve System:- (https://www.federalreserve.gov/releases/h10/Hist/dat00_uk.htm).The dataset has two variables Date and Rate (GBP/USD exchange rate). It is a daily data recording GBP/USD exchange rate from the year 2000 to April 15 2020. It has 5092 observations after removing the missing values. The missing data represents that the market is closed for that day. There are around 252 data points for each year.For computational purpose, I have selected only 300 subset of the dataset i.e.foreign exchange rate around the year 2010 and 2011. The economic market was quite stable at that time.

  • We write \({N_t,t=1,\dots,T}\) for the data.

Figure 1. Time Series of Original Data

  • Figure 1 (above) shows the times series plot of the whole data set. There is a sharp decrease in the year 2008, which was caused by the Financial Crisis.

Figure 2. Time Series of Used Data

  • Figure 2 shows a subset of 300 data points, it covers the year from 2010 and 2011. It is represented by a healthy market. For convenience of computation, we use 0 to 300 to represent the time. Eventhough there are many fluctuations in this time interval. Overall, there is an increasing trend.

4 Mathematical Modal

4.1 Geometric Brownian Motion (GBM) Model

Geometric Brownian Motion Model means the logarithm of the data follows a Brownian motion and provided the following equations(Brewer, K., Feng, Y., & Kwan, C, 2016). * The original differential equation is defined as \[ dN = \mu Ndt+\delta Ndz\] where \(N\) is the foreign exchange rate on that day, \(dz=\epsilon \sqrt{dt}\) and \(\epsilon\) is a random draw from the normal distribution with mean 0 and variance \(\sigma\). \(\mu\) and \(\delta\) are usually the drift parameter and the volatility parameter, respectively.
* The equation is equal to \[ d\log(N) = (\mu -\frac{\delta ^2}{2})dt+\delta dz\] * On solving the differential equation, we get \[ N_{t+\Delta{t}}=N_{t}e^{(\mu -\frac{\delta ^2}{2})\Delta{t}+\delta \epsilon \sqrt{\Delta{t}}}\] Set \(\Delta{t}\) equal to 1, we get \[ N_{t+1}=N_{t}e^{(\mu -\frac{\delta ^2}{2})\frac{1}{n}+\frac{\delta }{\sqrt{n}}\epsilon }\] where \(n\) is the number of days in a year, which is 252 (only open market days are taken).

4.2 Parameter Description

  • Follwoing are 3 parameters \(\mu\), \(\delta\) and \(\sigma\).
  • \(\mu\) is the drift parameter that shows the increasing or decreasing trend.
  • \(\delta\) is the volatility parameter that measures the deviations from the mean.
  • \(\sigma\) is the variance of the state parameter \(\epsilon\). By increasing sigma, it will increase the deviations from the mean.

5 POMP Model

5.1 Building POMP Model

  • The rprocess is based on the GBM model with two state variables, \(N\) and \(\epsilon\).
  • The parameters are \(\mu\), \(\sigma\) and \(\delta\).
  • The initial value of N is drawn from a random poisson distribution with mean 1.5. The initial value of \(\epsilon\) is drawn from a poisson distribution with mean 1.
  • The rmeasure is defined as Rate being drawn from a random draw from the normal distribution with mean 0 and variance \(N\), which is the state variable.
  • Implementation is shown below.
dmeas <- Csnippet("lik = dnorm(Rate,0,N,give_log);")
rmeas <- Csnippet("Rate = rnorm(0,N);")
Ne_initializer <- ("N=rpois(1.5);e=rpois(1);")
stochStep <- Csnippet("
                      e = rnorm(0,sigma);
                      N = N*exp((mu-delta*delta/2)/260+delta/sqrt(260)*e);
                      ")

stopifnot(packageVersion("pomp")>="0.75-1")
fx <- pomp(data = dt2,
     times="Date",
     t0=0,
     rprocess=discrete_time(step.fun=stochStep,delta.t=1),
     rmeasure = rmeas,
     dmeasure=dmeas, 
     obsnames = "Rate",
     partrans = parameter_trans(log=c("delta","sigma")),
     paramnames=c("mu","delta","sigma"),
     statenames=c("N","e"),
     rinit=Csnippet(Ne_initializer)
     )

8 Iterated Filtering on Data

8.1 Maximization and Likelihood Evaluation

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  -570.1  -569.9  -569.8  -569.8  -569.7  -569.5

The Local Maximum Search gives us a maximum of likelihood of -569.5 with a standard error of 0.007.

We can see that random walks are assigned to all 3 paramters mu, sigma and delta. Also the model is fitting the data well. The log-likelihood is increases initially and tends to separate to different values, indicating more iterations are required for a better result. All 3 parameters tends to separate values, while for each of the value we can observe a converging behavior.

8.2 Likelihood Surface Evaluation

Figure 6. Pairwise Plot

The pairwise plot in Figure 6 shows us the geometry of the likelihood surface in a neighborhood (20 units around the maximum likelihood) for each parameter. I perform global search to see if the result is stable and compare the likelihood with the GARCH model.

9 Global Search with Randomized Starting Values

9.1 Iterated Filtering with randomized starting values

For our data, the randomized starting values could be chosen from the following box. There are 3 parameters.We then carry out search identical to the local one except for the starting parameter values. This is coded by calling mif2 on previously constructed object if1[[1]], with a reset starting value:

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  -569.1  -569.0  -569.0  -569.0  -569.0  -569.0

This serach took 120 minutes. Parameter estimation requires many and random starting values. Now I draw a starting value uniformly from an interval for each parameter. If the estimation gives stable result with different starting values, then it will provide confidence that an adequate global search has been carried out (Ionizes, E., 2016).It gives us a best likelihood of -569.0 with a standard error of 0.008. The likelihood is similar to our local search and the global search provides a quite stable statistic.

The log-likelihood is increases initially and tends to separate to different values, indicating more iterations are required for a better result.All 3 parameters i.e mu, sigma and delta tends to separate values, while for each of the value we can observe a converging behavior.

9.2 Global Geometry of the likelihood surface

Figure 7. Pairwise Plot

The pairwise plot in Figure 7 shows, how does the geometry of the likelihood surface look like in the neighborhood (10 units around the maximum likelihood) for each parameter. We see optimization attempts from diverse remote starting points can approach on MLE, but do not exceed it. This gives us resonable confidence in our MLE. The points are clustered and end up with comparable likelihoods though the parameters are drawn from different starting values. It indicates that the model gives stable maximization of likelihood.

10 GARCH Model

10.1 Model Description

  • According to notes from the class, the GARCH(p,q) model has the form \[ Y_n = \epsilon_n \sqrt{V_n},\] where \[ V_n = \alpha_0 + \sum_{j=1}^p \alpha_j Y_{n-j}^2 + \sum_{k=1}^q \beta_k V_{n-k}\] and \(\epsilon_{1:N}\) is white noise (Ionides E., 2016).

GARCH is Generalized AutoRegressive Conditional Heteroskedasticity model where the variance error is believed to be serially autocorrelated. It assumes that the variance of error term follows autoregressive moving average process.From comparing the GARCH(1,0), GARCH(0,1) and GARCH(1,1) model by checking their log likelihoods, I choose to implement the GARCH(0,1) model as it gives the largest likelihood.

10.2 Log Likelihood

## 'log Lik.' -560.0184 (df=2)

The GARCH(0,1) model gives the log likelihood of -560.0184. It is slightly larger than than the log likelihood from the POMP model. This shows the likelihood does not change significantly between the POMP model and GARCH model. Since, the GARCH model is difficult to interpret, POMP model can be favored. However we can still need to use some preliminary results to see if it can be improved to beat the GARCH model.

10.3 Diagnostic Plots

Figure 10. Diagnostics Plots

The QQ-plot in Figure 10 (LHS) shows the residuals are normally distributed. The ACF plot in Figure 10 (RHS) shows 2 lags very slightly falling outside the dashed line. Since most autocorrelation values are within the confidence lines, we do not reject the assumption that errors are independent and follows Gaussian white noise model.

11 Conclusion

In this time series analysis, I have used the Geometric Brownian Motion to build a POMP model on the foreign exchange rate (GBP/USD).The POMP model gives a stable maximum log likelihood of -569.5. It shows that the GBM POMP model is suitable for the GBP/USD exchange rate data. GARCH(0,1) model is taken as a benchmark for comparison. The GARCH(0,1) model gives the log likelihood of -560.0184, which is slightly larger than the POMP model. POMP model can be prefered since GARCH is difficult to interpret (black-box model) and does not improve the likelihood significantly. GARCH may be useful for forecasting but it wont help us understand about how Foreign exchange work. However further preliminary analysis is necessary to improve the POMP model.

12 Limitations and Further Work

Here the POMP has two states and three parameters. More states could be introduced into the POMP model such as states recording the gross domestic product of the two countries. Further investigation could be conducted to find a mathematical formula to incorporate other factors into Geometric Brownian Motion model.
